# Flask Patterns

## Style and Conventions
- Follow PEP 8 and Ruff defaults
- Use 4-space indentation and keep lines under 100 characters
- Prefer explicit names and type hints for public interfaces
- Use `snake_case` for functions/variables and `PascalCase` for classes
- Prefer guard clauses (`return if ...`) over nested conditionals
- Prefer keyword arguments for semantic clarity
- Avoid abbreviations; use explicit and consistent names
- Use module-level docstrings for non-trivial modules
- Follow `ruff` and `mypy` conventions for linting and typing
- Write comments only when they add real value or context

## Structural Analysis and Code Reuse
- Analyze the overall project structure before creating or changing files
- Check whether existing packages, modules, or services can be reused or extended
- Avoid duplication; prefer refactoring and modularity (`utils`, service layer, domain modules)
- Move reusable logic to coherent locations (for example `app/services`, `app/domain`, `app/lib`)
- Keep architectural consistency across similar modules (API, auth, external integrations)

## Architectural Design
- Keep route handlers skinny; move business logic to services/domain layer
- Use schema-based validation for complex request payloads
- Avoid hidden side effects in ORM hooks; prefer explicit services/events
- Follow the Single Responsibility Principle for each class
- Ensure enums and constants have clear names aligned to business logic

## Service Objects
- Use class-based or function-based services with explicit input/output contracts
- Keep orchestration in services; keep persistence in repositories/models
- Return meaningful values or typed result objects (`success`, `error`, `data`)
- Namespace by domain: `surveys/check_automatic_assignments.py`

## Authorization
- Centralize authorization checks in policy/permission modules
- Every protected endpoint must check permissions explicitly
- Prefer role + resource-based checks over ad-hoc conditionals

## Data and Persistence
- Keep SQLAlchemy models focused on persistence concerns
- Use Alembic migrations for schema changes; one concern per migration
- Apply indexes for high-traffic filters, joins, and sort paths

## API Design
- Group endpoints by Blueprint and version (e.g. `api.v1.users`)
- Keep response contracts stable and documented in OpenAPI
- Use consistent pagination/filter/query conventions across endpoints

## Redis and Async Jobs
- Keep Redis access behind adapters/services to avoid scattered raw calls
- Use TTL for cached data and idempotency keys for critical workflows
- Use Celery/RQ for background jobs; keep job payloads small and serializable

## Frontend Integration (Next.js)
- Keep backend contract-friendly for Next.js server actions and edge/client fetch
- Use explicit cache headers and ETag when useful for incremental rendering
- Document auth flow for SSR and client-side transitions

## I18n
- Follow the existing translation-copy methodology used in this project
- Use structured, consistent keys (for example `users.form.email_label`)
- Do not hardcode user-facing text in templates, views, or API error strings
- Keep locale files ordered and consistent across supported languages

## Testing and Quality
- Write clear pytest tests, usually one file per module/domain unit
- Always cover business logic and critical services
- Prefer behavior-oriented tests for end-to-end user flows
- Keep test coverage high for meaningful commits

## Security and Configuration
- Use secret manager or environment variables for all secrets and system tokens
- Always validate and sanitize request payloads with schemas
- Do not expose stack traces or sensitive error messages in production
- Follow secure defaults: escaping, CSRF/session protections (if cookie auth), controlled logging
- Keep authentication and authorization patterns secure and well-documented

## AI Behavior for Cursor
- Analyze project structure before proposing changes
- Check for reusable patterns before writing new code
- Follow PEP 8 + Ruff + mypy when generating or editing code
- Ask for confirmation before changing core system components
- Generate concise, meaningful names and descriptions for new files, classes, and methods
- Add a brief rationale when making significant refactors
- Keep comments in Italian when required by team convention; keep code and names in English
- Do not add new dependencies without a clear reason
- Preserve consistency in naming, directory structure, and Flask conventions
